answer.para:
Pass &opt-M; to the &rt; (&lisp-run;
  or lisp.exe).
  Or, better yet, use the driver clisp (or
  clisp.exe) instead of invoking the &rt;
  directly.

The above code does not conform to &ansi-cl;, therefore &clisp;
  can produce arbitrary results.
  See .

E.g., &clisp; &directory; is different from the &cmucl;
 implementation, so, to find out how to get the results you want,
 you should search the &clisp; implementation notes for "DIRECTORY".
